dp:Data_Product_Port a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Data Product Port"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "A data product exposes ports; ports implement interfaces; contracts reference interfaces." ;
    rdfs:subClassOf [ a owl:Restriction ;
            owl:onClass dp:Data_Product ;
            owl:onProperty dp:is_port_of ;
            owl:qualifiedCardinality "1"^^xsd:nonNegativeInteger ],
        dp:Catalog_Asset ;
    skos:definition "A Data Port is a formally defined interface through which a data product exposes or consumes data, metadata, or services. It specifies how a data product can be accessed or integrated—such as through files, APIs, queries, or event streams—without exposing internal implementation details. Data ports provide a clear contract that includes access method, structure, semantics, and applicable governance constraints. In a data-product architecture, ports enable interoperability between products and bounded contexts while supporting independent evolution. When combined with Semantic Knowledge Graphs, data ports are often described using explicit semantic models, allowing their inputs, outputs, and constraints to be understood and validated consistently across the enterprise." ;
    dp:embedding_note """Data Product Port is a kind of Catalog Asset.
Query Port is a kind of Data Product Port.
Input Port is a kind of Data Product Port.
Operational Port is a kind of Data Product Port.
Output Port is a kind of Data Product Port.
Platform Port is a kind of Data Product Port.
Data Product Port rdfs:comment A data product exposes ports; ports implement interfaces; contracts reference interfaces.
Data Product Port has label Data Product Port.
Data Product Port has definition A Data Port is a formally defined interface through which a data product exposes or consumes data, metadata, or services. It specifies how a data product can be accessed or integrated—such as through files, APIs, queries, or event streams—without exposing internal implementation details. Data ports provide a clear contract that includes access method, structure, semantics, and applicable governance constraints. In a data-product architecture, ports enable interoperability between products and bounded contexts while supporting independent evolution. When combined with Semantic Knowledge Graphs, data ports are often described using explicit semantic models, allowing their inputs, outputs, and constraints to be understood and validated consistently across the enterprise."""@en .

dp:Port_Implementation a owl:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Port Implementation"@en ;
    rdfs:comment "An implementation artifact (code, service, or configuration) that realizes a data product port."@en ;
    rdfs:subClassOf dp:Catalog_Asset ;
    skos:definition "A Port  Implementation is the concrete realization of a Data Port in a working system, where models are instantiated using specific technologies, tools, and configurations." ;
    dp:embedding_note """Port Implementation is a kind of Catalog Asset.
Port Implementation rdfs:comment An implementation artifact (code, service, or configuration) that realizes a data product port.
Port Implementation has label Port Implementation.
Port Implementation has definition A Port  Implementation is the concrete realization of a Data Port in a working system, where models are instantiated using specific technologies, tools, and configurations."""@en .

